Ask HN: Where can I discuss random ideas?
text:
I often have a thought or insight and I want to have a conversation about it with interested people. Usually the quality of discussion is best on HN. Sometimes you get a good response to an Ask HN, sometimes it doesn't feel like the right place to post it.

I always struggle to find the best place to generate the best discussion. It's like its spread across Reddit, Discord, Slack, HackerNews, Twitter, etc.

Anyone else struggle with this?

Ask HN: Why isn't there something like Let's Encrypt for document signing?
text:
Considering how easy it is to generate a public/private key pair it's not that easy and not cheap to get an widely trusted document signing certificate. Especially one with LTV (longtime valid for verifying)

Is this just the market monopoly? If letsencrypt broke it for SSL, couldn't it be done for PDF signing also?

Ask HN: No Job Timezone
text:
I'm 45, have been a software engineer for over 25 years. I've worked backend java from the late 90s, perl, php, python, golang...

I've worked front-end React, angular, Vue, Android...

I've deployed lamdas, edge, rabbitmq clusters and all...

I've designed hundreds of systems for high availibility, low latency, under big stress conditions.

Yet, being located where I am, I struggle to find a job. Timezone is a major issue for most employers.

What would you suggest ?

17 years ago, I decided to settle in Cambodia. I have a wife and son here, relocating is out of the question. It's been harder and harder go find income sources.

title: Want some free NFC tags? We have some
text:
To celebrate our launch on Product Hunt this week we would like to offer you some of our NFC tags for free.

So here is the deal...

Vitag is a NFC system we created that makes it easy to add video instructions (and more) to anything so anyone can instantly see them with a tap of their phone; no app or QR code required.

Think of them as video sticky notes.

You can see the details over at Product Hunt https://www.producthunt.com/posts/vitag

Because we need your input on what we are building, we want to make it easy for you to try it out at no cost; no shipping charge, no credit card. Nada.

1. Just to to https://vitag.site/discount/PHStarter2022?redirect=%2Fcollections%2Fstarter-packs

2. Pick a card pack from our pre-printed NFC cards.

3. And check out (use discount code PHStarter2022 and you pay $0).

So what's the catch?

The cards work with our free app (iPhone & Android) that allows you to add content (including video) to the tags. And yes, the tags are locked, available in the USA only, and limited to one free order per person.

However, you can stick the tags on walls or desks and the app is cool and doesn't cost anything and has a ton of features.

This is not a sales pitch (kinda, but not really), all we need is people using the product and then telling us what we need to do to make it better for you.

Will we charge for it in the future? Yes, but right now, no. And no, you are not obligated to buy it in the future. Seriously, we are trying to make this risk-free and easy for you.

So what can you do with them?

When you go to https://vitag.site/discount/PHStarter2022?redirect=%2Fcollections%2Fstarter-packs you will see we have a lot of different types of use-cases we are targeting. Of course, Learn More tags are pretty generic but we also have tags for Wifi. Take a look.

Next, in the app, you can add content to the tags including video, links, text, wifi instructions or even (and this is coming out in a few days) redirect the tag to a URL you specify.

Even better, we built-in reporting so you can see when a tag is scanned and what they did with the info on the tag.

And for everyone that already has an NFC tag, we have a utility in the app so you can format it to work with our app (basically, use any NFC tag you want with the app).

So if you are interested and want to try it out for free, then great.

Otherwise thank you for reading this far. We love NFC technology and hope you do as well.

Sean Jackson

UK house prices set to plummet by 60%
text:
The UK government has flat out refused to get involved in the private mortgage markets, despite calls from housing experts and economists to intervene in the face of the predicted downturn in house prices.

According to a report by the UK Housing Association, house prices in certain areas of the country are predicted to drop by as much as 60% in 2023, with the South and North West set to be hit the hardest. The report has sparked concerns that the middle classes, in particular, will be hit hard by the downturn, with many facing negative equity as a result of the falling prices.

However, despite these concerns, the government has stated that it has no plans to intervene in the private mortgage markets. In a statement, a spokesperson for the government said: "We believe that the private mortgage market should be allowed to operate freely and without interference from the government. Intervention would only serve to distort the market and could have unintended consequences for both homeowners and the economy as a whole."

The decision has been met with criticism from some quarters, with many arguing that the government has a responsibility to protect homeowners and prevent a potential economic downturn. "The government's refusal to intervene in the mortgage market is short-sighted and irresponsible," said Samantha Jones, Chief Economist at the UK Housing Association. "If house prices continue to fall, it could have a devastating impact on the economy and on the lives of many middle-class homeowners. The government must act now to support the housing market and prevent a potential crisis."

Despite the criticism, it seems that the government is unlikely to change its stance on the issue, leaving many homeowners in uncertain times ahead.
